        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1962-04-26T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1962-04-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="169"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d169">
                <head>169. Memorandum From the Naval Aide to the Presidentʼs Military Representative
                        (<persName corresp="#p_BWH1" type="from">Bagley</persName>) to the
                    Presidentʼs Military Representative (<persName corresp="#p_TMD1" type="to"
                        >Taylor</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d169fn1">Source:
                        National Defense University, <persName corresp="#p_TMD1">Taylor</persName>
                        Papers, T-132-69. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1962-04-26">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 26, 1962</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Viet-Nam Task Force Meeting, 25 April 1962</item>
                </list>
                <p>Meeting was devoted to a briefing by Mr. <persName corresp="#p_CSJ3"
                        >Cottrell</persName> on his recent 2-day visit to Saigon with General
                        <persName>LeMay</persName>.<note n="2" xml:id="d169fn2">
                        <persName>LeMay</persName> visited Vietnam April 16-21. It is unclear from
                        his report of April 24 which of these days he spent in Saigon. (Washington
                        National Records Center, RG 330, OSD Files: FRC 66 A 3542, Vietnam 1962, 320
                        thru 370.05)</note>
                </p>
                <p>The main points made were: <list>
                        <label>a.</label>
                        <item>
                            <p>There is confusion on both the <gloss target="#t_GVN1">GVN</gloss>
                                and US side in Saigon, apparently due to organizational
                                uncertainties. The Ambassador and <gloss target="#t_DCM1"
                                    >DCM</gloss> have had long recent conversations with <persName
                                    corresp="#p_NDN1">Nhu</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_NDT2"
                                    >Thuan</persName> and are hopeful of some progress in clearing
                                lines of command. <persName corresp="#p_CSJ3">Cottrell</persName> is
                                mulling over the idea of using lower administrative levels as the
                                point of contact for advice. … Mr. <persName corresp="#p_TWC2"
                                    >Trueheart</persName> (<gloss target="#t_DCM1">DCM</gloss>)
                                thought this would be difficult to do in other ministries.</p>
                            <pb facs="0364" n="344" xml:id="pg_344"/>
                            <p>
                                <persName corresp="#p_CSJ3">Cottrell</persName> asked <persName
                                    corresp="#p_NDT2">Thuan</persName> why the <gloss
                                    target="#t_GVN1">GVN</gloss> had not asked for US advisors per
                                the joint December Memorandum of Understanding.<note n="3"
                                    xml:id="d169fn3">See the enclosure to <persName
                                        corresp="#p_NFEJ1">Nolting</persName>ʼs letter to <persName
                                        corresp="#p_NDD2">Diem</persName>, <ref
                                        target="frus1961-63v01#d307">
                                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1961–1963, vol. I,
                                        Document 307</ref>.</note>
                                <persName corresp="#p_NDT2">Thuan</persName> implied concern with
                                past experiences with advisors from Michigan State, and preferred to
                                continue profitable contacts with institutions such as Brookings,
                                who were giving them useful studies. The obvious impression was that
                                there were enough US advisors in <gloss target="#t_SVN1">SVN</gloss>
                                without formalizing specific positions.</p>
                            <p>(There is a renewed State interest in the whole matter of US advice;
                                the extent to which it is needed and the probable results if it is
                                not accepted by the <gloss target="#t_GVN1">GVN</gloss>.)</p>
                        </item>
                        <label>b.</label>
                        <item>
                            <persName corresp="#p_CSJ3">Cottrell</persName> is impressed with the
                            execution of air support in <gloss target="#t_SVN1">SVN</gloss>, both US
                            and <gloss target="#t_GVN1">GVN</gloss>. (This is a complete switch
                            based on his look on the ground and talks with Gen. LeMay.)</item>
                        <label>c.</label>
                        <item>
                            <persName corresp="#p_CSJ3">Cottrell</persName> backs selective
                            defoliation, including against <gloss target="#t_VC1">VC</gloss> crops,
                            and thinks the chemicals will do the job against food crops. (This is
                            also a 180 degree turn resulting from talks with <persName
                                corresp="#p_NDD2">Diem</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_TWC2"
                                >Trueheart</persName>; the reason for his confidence in the
                            chemicals is not clear.) He recognizes some political hazards, but
                            considers them acceptable for the gains involved.</item>
                        <label>d.</label>
                        <item>He talked with Mr. <persName>Walton</persName>, the <gloss
                                target="#t_USOM1">USOM</gloss> police advisor. You will recall
                                <persName>Walton</persName> was very critical last fall of the
                            situation in <gloss target="#t_SVN1">SVN</gloss>. He now thinks there is
                            real improvement; the police link with the Surete is good, and equipment
                            and training facilities are improved.</item>
                        <label>e.</label>
                        <item>US advisors to Province Chiefs are in place in 11 provinces. <persName
                                corresp="#p_NDD2">Diem</persName> is pushing for helos and vehicles
                            for provinces so the chiefs can get around; some have not visited the
                            greater majority of their villages because of the security
                            situation.</item>
                        <label>f.</label>
                        <item>Implementation of <persName corresp="#p_SEA2">Staley</persName>
                            reforms has produced <gloss target="#t_GVN1">GVN</gloss> budget
                            shortages. <gloss target="#t_AID1">AID</gloss> and State are studying
                            this matter to see what can be done. A prime factor is a general
                            let-down in business activity.</item>
                        <label>g.</label>
                        <item>In a talk with Gen. LeMay, <persName corresp="#p_NDD2">Diem</persName>
                            produced a long shopping list of items desired. Included were jet T-33
                            aircraft, radars, ULA helicopters for province use, photo processing
                            facility, air photo capability.<note n="4" xml:id="d169fn4">A summary
                                account of this meeting is in LeMayʼs final report; see <ref
                                    target="#d169fn2">footnote 2</ref> above.</note>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>As a separate but related matter, I understand at the JCS meeting 25 April,<note
                        n="5" xml:id="d169fn5">No record of this meeting has been found.</note> Gen.
                    LeMay said the Army was not employing air support in <gloss target="#t_SVN1"
                        >SVN</gloss> often enough in routine and set-piece operations though for
                    reaction type missions it is well used. He noted there is significant unused air
                    capacity. He complained that his people could not get by the Chief of Staff
                    (Marine Gen. Weede) to talk this over with Gen. <persName corresp="#p_HGPD1"
                        >Harkins</persName>. (Gen. LeMay talked with Gen. <persName
                        corresp="#p_HGPD1">Harkins</persName> in Saigon so presumably this matter is
                    resolved.) Reportedly, Gen. <persName corresp="#p_SGDM1">Shoup</persName> said
                    if the senior <pb facs="0365" n="345" xml:id="pg_345"/> Air Force officers in
                    Saigon were not man enough to insist on seeing the Commander on a vital issue we
                    were in greater difficulty there than he had thought.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BWH1">
                            <hi rend="strong">W.H.B.</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="6" xml:id="d169fn6">Printed from a copy that bears these typed
                            initials.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
